Before you waste your time resubmitting...

A motion to dismiss is completely the wrong avenue to argue that the "Defendant [had] legal authority or justification to arrest‚Äîand
therefore restrain‚Äîthe Plaintiff."

The Complaint alleges facts that, if assumed true, would lead to the conclusion that the Defendant was not acting with legal justification. It is common knowledge for any law school graduate that, while reviewing a motion to dismiss, courts must accept as true all factual allegations in the complaint and construe the complaint liberally. E.g., Settles v. U.S. Parole Comm‚Äôn, 429 F.3d 1098, 1106 (D.C. Cir. 2005).
